          <physDesc>
            <p>Vellum, about 8 7/8 in. by 6, consisting of 113 leaves, some of which are slightly stained and torn, especially foll. 1—3, 25, 60, and 64. The quires, the number of which is uncertain, were originally signed with arithmetical figures (fol. 38 a, %). They must have fallen into confusion at an early period, and have been renumbered, often incorrectly, by at least two hands, with Syriac letters at the foot of the page and Coptic letters at the top. Leaves are now wanting at the beginning and end, as well as after foll. 4, 8, 13, 19, 24, 32, 34, 52, 58, 59, 64, 95, 101, and 107. Each page is divided into two columns, of from 26 to 42 lines.</p>
